Docker Revision + 20 Interview Questions

Quick Revision — Core Concepts
1. Docker Architecture

Developer CLI
     │
     ▼
Docker Daemon (dockerd)      ← manages everything
     │
     ├─── Images             ← read-only templates (layers)
     ├─── Containers         ← running instances of images
     ├─── Volumes            ← persistent storage
     └─── Networks           ← container communication

Container Registry (Docker Hub / Artifactory)
     │
     └─── push/pull images

2. Image Layers
FROM ubuntu:22.04         ← Layer 1 (base, ~77MB)
RUN apt-get install python ← Layer 2 (added packages)
COPY app.py /app/          ← Layer 3 (your code)
CMD ["python", "/app/app.py"] ← Layer 4 (metadata only)

Each layer is IMMUTABLE and CACHED
Changing Layer 2 → invalidates Layer 3, 4 (cache busted)

3. Dockerfile Key Instructions
FROM        # base image
RUN         # execute command during build (creates layer)
COPY        # copy files from host into image
ADD         # like COPY but also handles URLs and tar auto-extract
ENV         # runtime environment variable
ARG         # build-time variable only
EXPOSE      # documents port (does NOT publish it)
VOLUME      # declares mount point
WORKDIR     # sets working directory
USER        # sets runtime user
CMD         # default command (overridable)
ENTRYPOINT  # fixed executable (use --entrypoint to override)
LABEL       # metadata key=value
HEALTHCHECK # how Docker checks if container is healthy

4. Essential Commands
# Images
docker build -t myapp:1.0 .
docker images
docker pull nginx:alpine
docker push myregistry/myapp:1.0
docker rmi myapp:1.0
docker image prune -a          # remove all unused images

# Containers
docker run -d -p 8080:80 --name webserver nginx
docker ps                      # running
docker ps -a                   # all including stopped
docker stop webserver
docker rm webserver
docker logs webserver -f       # follow logs
docker exec -it webserver sh   # shell into running container
docker inspect webserver       # full metadata JSON

# Volumes
docker volume create mydata
docker run -v mydata:/data alpine
docker volume ls
docker volume prune

# Networks
docker network create mynet
docker run --network mynet alpine
docker network ls
docker network inspect mynet

5. Volumes vs Bind Mounts vs tmpfs
Named Volume          Bind Mount            tmpfs
─────────────         ──────────────        ──────────────
Managed by Docker     You control path      RAM only
Portable              Host-dependent        Lost on stop
docker volume create  -v /host:/container   --tmpfs /tmp
Best for production   Best for dev          Best for secrets/temp

6. Networking Types
bridge   ← default, containers on same host talk via virtual switch
host     ← container shares host network stack (no isolation)
none     ← no networking
overlay  ← multi-host (Docker Swarm)
macvlan  ← container gets its own MAC/IP on physical network

7. Multi-Stage Build
# Stage 1: Build (heavy — compiler, dev deps)
FROM node:20 AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm ci
COPY . .
RUN npm run build

# Stage 2: Runtime (minimal — only what runs)
FROM node:20-alpine AS runtime
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=builder /app/dist ./dist
COPY --from=builder /app/node_modules ./node_modules
USER node
CMD ["node", "dist/index.js"]

# Result: production image has NO compiler, NO dev tools, NO source

8. Docker Compose
services:
  app:
    build: .
    ports: ["3000:3000"]
    environment:
      - NODE_ENV=production
    depends_on:
      db:
        condition: service_healthy
    networks: [backend]
    volumes: [appdata:/data]

  db:
    image: postgres:15-alpine
    environment:
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: secret
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "pg_isready", "-U", "postgres"]
      interval: 10s
      retries: 5
    volumes: [dbdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data]
    networks: [backend]

volumes:
  appdata:
  dbdata:

networks:
  backend:

9. Security Summary
❌ Running as root          → USER appuser / USER 10001
❌ Secrets in ENV/ARG       → --mount=type=secret / runtime -e
❌ Unscanned images         → trivy image --severity HIGH,CRITICAL
❌ Writable filesystem      → --read-only --tmpfs /tmp
❌ All capabilities          → --cap-drop ALL --cap-add <only needed>
❌ Shell form ENTRYPOINT    → ["exec", "form"] for PID 1 signals

10. Health Check
HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=10s --retries=3 \
  CMD curl -f http://localhost:3000/health || exit 1

docker inspect <container> | grep -A5 Health
# "Status": "healthy" / "unhealthy" / "starting"

docker ps   # shows (healthy) or (unhealthy) in STATUS column

20 Interview Questions
Q1: What is the difference between an image and a container?

An image is a read-only template (blueprint). A container is a running instance of that image — it adds a thin writable layer on top. Multiple containers can run from the same image simultaneously.

Q2: What happens when you run docker build?

Docker reads the Dockerfile top-to-bottom, executes each instruction as a separate layer, caches each layer by its content hash. If an instruction changes, that layer and all subsequent layers are rebuilt. The final result is a tagged image stored locally.

Q3: What is a Docker layer and why does layer caching matter?

Each RUN, COPY, ADD creates an immutable layer. Layers are cached by content. If you change COPY app.py, Docker replays from that point — not from the start. Best practice: put frequently changing instructions (COPY code) at the bottom, rarely changing ones (install dependencies) at the top to maximize cache hits.

Q4: What is the difference between COPY and ADD?

Both copy files into the image. ADD additionally:

Auto-extracts .tar archives
Accepts remote URLs
Use COPY by default — it is explicit and predictable. Use ADD only when you specifically need tar-extraction.

Q5: What is the difference between CMD and ENTRYPOINT?

ENTRYPOINT defines the fixed executable that always runs. CMD provides default arguments to it, easily overridden at docker run. Combined: ENTRYPOINT ["python"] + CMD ["app.py"] → runs python app.py by default, but docker run myimage other.py runs python other.py.

Q6: What is exec form vs shell form and why does it matter?

Exec form ["python", "app.py"] — runs directly, process is PID 1, receives SIGTERM → graceful shutdown works
Shell form python app.py — runs as /bin/sh -c python app.py, sh is PID 1, your app never gets SIGTERM → docker stop waits 10s then kills forcefully
Q7: What is the difference between ARG and ENV?

ARG is available only during the build (docker build --build-arg). It is gone at runtime. ENV is set at build time and persists into the running container. To make a build value available at runtime: ARG VER=1.0 then ENV VERSION=$VER.

Q8: What is a multi-stage build and why use it?

A Dockerfile with multiple FROM instructions. Each stage is independent. You copy only the compiled artifacts from the builder stage into the final minimal image. Benefits: smaller production image (no compiler/dev tools), smaller attack surface, faster pulls.

Q9: What is the difference between a named volume and a bind mount?

Named volume — managed by Docker, stored in Docker's storage area, portable across systems, best for production data. Bind mount — maps a specific host path (-v /home/user/data:/data), host-dependent, best for development (live code editing).

Q10: How do containers communicate on the same Docker network?

Containers on the same bridge network can reach each other by container name as DNS hostname. Example: a web container reaches a db container at db:5432 if both are on the same network. Docker's embedded DNS resolves container names automatically.

Q11: What is EXPOSE in a Dockerfile?

EXPOSE 3000 is documentation only — it tells humans and tools which port the app listens on. It does NOT publish the port. To actually publish: docker run -p 8080:3000 maps host port 8080 to container port 3000.

Q12: What is the difference between docker stop and docker kill?

docker stop sends SIGTERM (graceful shutdown), waits 10 seconds, then sends SIGKILL. docker kill sends SIGKILL immediately (no grace period). Always prefer docker stop to allow the app to flush buffers, close DB connections, etc.

Q13: What is a distroless image?

An image with no OS shell, no package manager, no bash — only your app and its runtime. Produced by Google (gcr.io/distroless). Benefit: smallest possible attack surface — an attacker who breaks in has no tools to use. Drawback: very hard to debug interactively.

Q14: How does Trivy work and what does it scan?

Trivy scans the contents of an image's layers, extracts installed packages (OS + language), and cross-references them against CVE databases (NVD, GitHub Advisory). It also scans for secrets (API keys, tokens) and misconfigurations. --exit-code 1 --severity CRITICAL fails CI on critical findings.

Q15: Why should you never put secrets in ENV or ARG in a Dockerfile?

ENV values are visible in docker inspect and in the image manifest. ARG values are stored in the build cache and visible in docker history. Use BuildKit --mount=type=secret for build-time secrets, and runtime -e or mounted secret files for runtime secrets.

Q16: What is docker-compose depends_on and what is its limitation?

depends_on controls start order — it waits for the dependency container to start, NOT for it to be ready/healthy. A DB container starting is not the same as Postgres accepting connections. Use depends_on: condition: service_healthy combined with a healthcheck on the dependency to wait until it's actually ready.

Q17: What is the difference between docker-compose up and docker-compose up --build?

up starts containers using existing images (builds only if image doesn't exist yet). up --build always rebuilds images before starting. Use --build when you've changed the Dockerfile or source code and want the changes applied.

Q18: What is --read-only and --cap-drop ALL?

--read-only makes the container's root filesystem immutable — no files can be written (pair with --tmpfs /tmp for temp writes). --cap-drop ALL removes all Linux kernel capabilities from the container — prevents network config changes, ptrace debugging of other processes, etc. Add back only what's needed with --cap-add.

Q19: What is the HEALTHCHECK instruction and when is a container marked unhealthy?

HEALTHCHECK CMD curl -f http://localhost/health || exit 1 runs the command periodically. After --retries consecutive failures, the container is marked unhealthy. Docker doesn't automatically restart unhealthy containers — but orchestrators like Swarm and Kubernetes do. docker ps shows (unhealthy) in the STATUS column.

Q20: A container exits immediately after docker run. How do you debug it?
# See exit code and status
docker ps -a

# Check logs (even from stopped container)
docker logs <container_id>

# Override CMD to get a shell
docker run -it --entrypoint sh <image>

# Inspect the image to see what CMD/ENTRYPOINT was set
docker inspect <image> | grep -A5 Cmd

Common causes: app crashes on start, missing env var, missing file, wrong WORKDIR, permission denied (non-root user can't read files).> # See exit code and status
